==>PPI (Pixels Per Inch):

Refers to screen density — how many pixels fit into one inch of display.
Higher PPI = sharper images (e.g., smartphones often exceed 400 PPI).
Lower PPI = visible pixelation (older monitors ~72–96 PPI).
Property of the display, not the image itself.

DPI (Dots Per Inch):
Refers to printer density — how many ink dots are placed per inch of paper.
Common print standards:
300 DPI → professional-quality prints (books, photos).
600 DPI → high-end prints (business cards, fine detail).
150 DPI → acceptable for large banners viewed from afar.
Property of the printer, not the digital file.

==>Physical Pixel (Device Pixel):
The smallest hardware dot on a display.
Fixed count based on the screen’s resolution (e.g., a 1920×1080 monitor has 2,073,600 physical pixels).
Each pixel is made of sub-pixels (red, green, blue) that combine to show color.
Does not change regardless of scaling or zoom.

Logical Pixel (CSS Pixel / DIP):
A software abstraction used by operating systems and browsers.
Represents how content is measured and displayed in layouts.
Adjusts based on Device Pixel Ratio (DPR).
Example: On a 4K screen with DPR=2, a CSS width of 100px may render as 200 physical pixels.
Ensures consistent sizing across devices with different resolutions.

